ce:section.ce:para:
Numerous guanine-rich DNA sequences are predisposed to fold into four-stranded structures known as G-quadruplexes. Oligonucleotide sequence G5-DNA could fold into four-stranded structures induced by Pb2+ ions [25], the binding constant of Pb2+ ions with guanine-rich DNA strand was about 107 
                        [26,27]. The G-quadruplex formation was also confirmed with SH-DNA (thioglycolate G5) by QCM experiments. At the first stage, by injecting SH-DNA solution of various concentrations, the changes in frequency (f) and dissipation (D) for the grafting of thiol-terminated single stranded DNA on a gold-coated crystal surface at pH 7.4 were investigated, where the DNA chains have single chain structure (Fig. 3
                        ). The frequency decreasing was indicative of increasing the layer mass and supported that DNA chains have been grafted on a gold surface. On the other hand, it is known that D reflects the changes in the thickness and structure. Typically, a rigid and dense layer has small dissipation while a looser and thicker structure exhibits a larger dissipation. Increasing of D is indicative of increasing thickness of the DNA layer or the grafting of DNA. In the second stage, injecting Pb2+ ions solutions of various concentrations, f and D were found to increase and decrease quickly, respectively, because Pb2+ ions could change G5-DNA conformation to G-quadruplex that leads to the decrease of thickness and the dehydration of DNA chains [28].
